ITEM 1.

BUSINESS

OncoMed is a clinical-stage biopharmaceutical company focused on discovering and developing novel therapeutics that address the fundamental biology driving cancer’s growth, resistance, recurrence and metastasis.

We have eight therapeutic candidates currently in clinical development targeting cancer stem cell, or CSC, pathways and immuno-oncology, including our most recent Investigational New Drug, or IND, filing for our anti-TIGIT program. We plan to advance a ninth therapeutic candidate toward submission of an IND application with the U.S. Food and Drug Administration, or FDA, in the first half of 2017. All of the therapeutic candidates in our pipeline were discovered by OncoMed scientists, and we continue to pursue the discovery of additional novel therapeutic candidates. We have established a number of proprietary technologies to aid in ongoing drug discovery, candidate validation and predictive biomarker efforts. We have formed significant strategic alliances with Celgene Corporation, Bayer Pharma AG and GlaxoSmithKline and revenues from these collaborations have supported the advancement and growth of our pipeline.  The following summarizes the status of our therapeutic candidates and select preclinical programs, each of which will be described and discussed in further detail below under “—Our Therapeutic Candidates and Preclinical Programs.”

 

•

Demcizumab (Anti-DLL4, OMP-21M18). Demcizumab is a first-in-class humanized monoclonal antibody that inhibits Delta-like Ligand 4, or DLL4, in the Notch signaling pathway. Demcizumab is currently being evaluated in three clinical trials: a randomized Phase II trial in pancreatic cancer, a randomized Phase II trial in non-small cell lung cancer, or NSCLC, and a Phase Ib trial combining demcizumab and pembrolizumab (Keytruda®), an anti-Programmed Death-1, or anti-PD-1, antibody in solid tumor patients. The randomized Phase II clinical trial known as “YOSEMITE” of demcizumab in combination with standard-of-care gemcitabine plus Abraxane® (paclitaxel protein-bound particles for injectable suspension) (albumin bound) in first-line metastatic pancreatic cancer patients completed enrollment (n=207 randomized; 204 treated patients) in August 2016. Demcizumab has received orphan drug designation for pancreatic cancer from the FDA. OncoMed anticipates that certain top-line results, including response rate, median progression free survival and interim median overall survival, or OS, from the YOSEMITE trial will be available in the first half of 2017. Subsequent analyses of interim OS and final OS are planned for later in the year. The randomized Phase II clinical trial known as “DENALI” in patients with first-line non-squamous NSCLC is testing demcizumab in combination with standard-of-care carboplatin and pemetrexed.  We capped further enrollment in the DENALI clinical trial at 82 patients in November 2016 and plan to analyze data from the trial in the first half of 2017.  A Phase Ib trial assessing the combination of demcizumab plus pembrolizumab in solid tumor patients began enrolling patients in the dose-escalation portion of the trial in March 2016 and is now enrolling patients in expansion cohorts. Demcizumab is part of our strategic collaboration with Celgene Corporation, or Celgene, which is discussed below under “—Key Collaboration and License Agreements—Strategic Alliance with Celgene.” Celgene retains an option during certain time periods through the end of certain Phase II clinical trials to obtain an exclusive license to co-develop and co-commercialize demcizumab in the U.S. with us, sharing profits 50/50, while Celgene would lead development and commercialization outside the U.S.  If the initial results are positive, we anticipate submitting the demcizumab data package to Celgene for opt-in consideration during the first half of 2017.  The Phase II data from the YOSEMITE clinical trial are expected to form the basis of the data package. Data from the DENALI trial and interim data from the Phase Ib trial in combination with pembrolizumab are also expected to be submitted to Celgene to further support and inform an opt-in decision regarding demcizumab.  We would be entitled to a $70.0 million opt-in payment if Celgene exercises its option on demcizumab.  

4

 

 

•

Tarextumab (Anti-Notch2/3, OMP-59R5). Tarextumab is a first-in-class fully human monoclonal antibody that inhibits signaling by the Notch2 and Notch3 receptors and is currently being evaluated for the treatment of small cell lung cancer. We have completed enrollment of 145 patients with first-line extensive-stage small cell lung cancer in the Phase II portion of the clinical trial of tarextumab known as “PINNACLE”. The Phase II portion of the PINNACLE trial is designed to assess the safety and efficacy of tarextumab in combination with platinum-based chemotherapy and etoposide. Tarextumab has received orphan drug designation from the FDA for small cell lung cancer. We anticipate announcing top-line results from the Phase II portion of the PINNACLE trial in the first half of 2017, including response rates, median progression free survival, median overall survival, and certain biomarker analyses. Tarextumab is part of our collaboration with GlaxoSmithKline LLC, or GSK, which is discussed further below under “—Key Collaboration and License Agreements—Strategic Alliance with GSK.” GSK retains an option during a certain time period through the end of the PINNACLE trial to obtain an exclusive license to develop and commercialize tarextumab. Once data from the Phase II portion of the PINNACLE trial are available, we expect to submit the tarextumab data package to GSK in the first half of 2017. If GSK exercises its option on tarextumab, we would be entitled to receive a $25.0 million opt-in payment, and GSK would then lead and fully fund further development and commercialization of tarextumab.

 

•

Wnt pathway inhibitors - Vantictumab (Anti-Fzd, OMP-18R5) and Ipafricept (Fzd8-Fc, OMP-54F28). Vantictumab is a fully human monoclonal antibody that binds a conserved epitope on five Frizzled receptors and inhibits Wnt signaling. We believe vantictumab is the first monoclonal antibody designed to inhibit Wnt signaling to enter clinical testing. We are currently enrolling patients in two Phase Ib clinical trials of vantictumab in combination with standard-of-care chemotherapy in HER2-negative breast and pancreatic cancers. Ipafricept, our second therapeutic candidate targeting the Wnt pathway, is a proprietary first-in-class fusion protein based on a truncated form of the Frizzled 8 receptor, or Fzd8. We are also currently enrolling patients in two Phase Ib clinical trials of ipafricept in combination with standard-of-care chemotherapy, in platinum-sensitive ovarian and pancreatic cancers.

Vantictumab and ipafricept are part of our Wnt pathway collaboration with Bayer Pharma AG, or Bayer, which is discussed below under “—Key Collaboration and License Agreements—Strategic Alliance with Bayer.” Bayer retains an option through the earlier of completion of certain Phase I trials or a set date in June 2017 to obtain an exclusive license to develop and commercialize vantictumab and/or ipafricept. We plan to submit data packages to Bayer for the vantictumab and ipafricept programs in the first half of 2017 for opt-in consideration. The vantictumab and ipafricept data packages will include data from their Phase Ib clinical trials. If Bayer exercises one or both of its options, OncoMed would be entitled to receive a $25.0 million opt-in payment for vantictumab and a $15.0 million opt-in payment for ipafricept. Upon exercising its option for vantictumab and/or ipafricept, Bayer would then lead and fully fund further development and commercialization.

 

•

Navicixizumab (Anti-DLL4/VEGF Bispecific, OMP-305B83). Navicixizumab is our bispecific monoclonal antibody that targets and inhibits both DLL4 and vascular endothelial growth factor, or VEGF. We are currently completing a Phase Ia single-agent clinical trial of navicixizumab in patients with advanced solid tumors, and we have initiated two Phase Ib clinical trials to assess navicixizumab in combination with standard chemotherapy regimens in patients with platinum-resistant ovarian cancer and second line metastatic colorectal cancer. This program is part of our strategic collaboration with Celgene, which is discussed below under “—Key Collaboration and License Agreements—Strategic Alliance with Celgene.” Celgene retains an option during certain time periods through the end of certain Phase I clinical trials to obtain an exclusive license to co-develop and co-commercialize navicixizumab in the U.S. with us, sharing profits 50/50, while Celgene would lead development and commercialization outside the U.S.

 

•

Anti-RSPO3 (OMP-131R10). Anti-RSPO3 is a first-in-class monoclonal antibody targeting the RSPO-LGR cancer stem cell pathway. RSPO overexpression is associated with the growth of a number of solid tumors, including certain colorectal cancers. We are currently enrolling patients in a Phase Ia/b clinical trial and are using a CLIA-validated assay and a custom liquid biopsy test in this trial to identify tumors with RSPO3-high gene expression and gene fusions where responses to treatment may be more likely. The Phase Ia portion of the anti-RSPO3 clinical trial is in solid tumor patients, and enrollment in the dose-escalation portion of the Phase Ia portion of the clinical trial is complete. We are now enrolling

5

 

 

biomarker-selected patients in the Phase Ia expansion cohort. The Phase Ib portion of the clinical trial, which began enrolling patients in January 2016, is in certain colorectal cancer and gastric cancer patients who have high levels of the RSPO3 biomarker, in combination with standard-of-care folinic acid, fluorouracil and irinotecan, or FOLFIRI, chemotherapy. Programs in the RSPO-LGR pathway are part of our strategic collaboration with Celgene, which is discussed below under “—Key Collaboration and License Agreements—Strategic Alliance with Celgene.” Celgene retains an option during certain time periods through the end of certain Phase I clinical trials to obtain an exclusive license to co-develop and co-commercialize anti-RSPO3 in the U.S. with us, sharing profits 50/50, while Celgene would lead development and commercialization outside the U.S. Upon completion of certain enrollment objectives in the Phase I clinical trials, OncoMed plans to submit a data package to Celgene for opt-in consideration. If Celgene exercises its option on anti-RSPO3, OncoMed would be eligible for an approximately $37.8 million opt-in payment.

 

•

Brontictuzumab (Anti-Notch1, OMP-52M51). Brontictuzumab inhibits signaling of Notch1, an important CSC pathway implicated in chemoresistance, tumor angiogenesis and stem cell self-renewal, proliferation and differentiation. Notch1 signaling is prevalent in several solid tumor types, including certain breast, esophageal, colorectal, gastric, pancreatic and small cell lung cancers, as well as adenoid cystic carcinoma and cholangiocarcinoma. The combination of brontictuzumab with trifluridine/tipiracil (Lonsurf®) is currently being studied in a Phase Ib clinical trial in patients with metastatic colorectal cancer who have failed at least two prior treatment regimens. Once a maximum tolerated dose is identified, additional patients whose tumors test high for the activated form of Notch1 will be enrolled in an expansion cohort. OncoMed has worldwide rights to brontictuzumab.

 

•

Anti-TIGIT (OMP-313M32) T-cell immunoglobulin and ITIM domain protein, or TIGIT, is an inhibitory receptor that is thought to potentially stop T-cells from attacking certain tumor cells. In December 2016, we submitted an IND application with the FDA for anti-TIGIT, our antibody that binds to and inhibits TIGIT. Our IND application was subsequently cleared by the FDA and a Phase I clinical trial of anti-TIGIT is expected to begin enrolling patients during the first half of 2017. This program, previously known as “I/O#2”, is part of our Celgene collaboration, which is discussed below under “—Key Collaboration and License Agreements—Strategic Alliance with Celgene.” Upon the completion of certain enrollment criteria in the Phase I clinical trial, Celgene would have the option to obtain an exclusive license to develop and commercialize anti-TIGIT. If Celgene exercises its option on anti-TIGIT, OncoMed would be eligible for a $35.0 million opt-in payment and it is expected that Celgene would then lead and fully fund further development and commercialization.

 

•

GITRL-Fc trimer (OMP-336B11). Glucocorticoid-induced tumor necrosis factor receptor, or GITR, and its ligand, GITRL, are members of the tumor necrosis factor, or TNF, family of receptors and ligands.  TNF ligands are trimeric proteins and their binding leads to receptor clustering and activation of intracellular signaling.  Activation of GITR enhances T-cell modulated immune responses, which we believe makes it a promising target for stimulating immune system activity against tumor cells.  Our GITR ligand therapeutic candidate, GITRL-Fc, is engineered using a novel single-gene, linkerless trimer technology that is designed to enable effective activation of GITR.  In preclinical models, this design has achieved robust anti-tumor immune responses alone and in combination with other immuno-oncology agents.  This program is wholly owned by OncoMed, and we are planning to submit an IND application with the FDA for GITRL-Fc in the first half of 2017. OncoMed has worldwide rights to the GITRL-Fc trimer program.

We also have a number of ongoing drug discovery efforts to address biological pathways and targets that drive cancer’s growth, resistance, recurrence, and metastasis including multiple undisclosed immuno-oncology candidates. We believe these research efforts have the potential to produce multiple additional IND submissions in future years.  Data for all of our therapeutic candidates are being gathered to inform the advancement of these therapeutic candidates into later stage clinical trials independently or with our partners, with the goal of ultimately obtaining regulatory approvals and improving patient outcomes.

6

 

Strategy

We are focused on discovering and developing novel therapeutic candidates directed to fundamental biologic pathways and targets thought to drive cancer’s growth, resistance, recurrence and metastasis. We believe that a key reason for the limitations of many current cancer treatments is that they fail to impede the growth of CSCs, which are responsible for the initiation, metastasis and recurrence of many cancers. Additionally, the inability of the immune system to shut down tumor growth, through a series of tumor-associated resistance mechanisms, enables the growth and recurrence of cancers. We have discovered and advanced several therapeutic candidates specifically targeting cancer stem cell pathways and we have an emerging pipeline of immuno-oncology therapeutic candidates that aim to bolster immune system recognition of cancer cells and/or suppress immune system evasion mechanisms. Our goal is to build a leading biopharmaceutical company that discovers, develops and commercializes novel anti-CSC and immuno-oncology therapeutics. Key elements of our strategy to achieve this goal are:

 

•

Continue to discover and advance novel cancer therapeutics based on our proprietary discovery and drug development platform technologies. To date, our proprietary minimally-passaged human tumor bank, syngeneic and murine models and antibody engineering platforms have led to the discovery of nine proprietary therapeutic candidates that are currently being evaluated in clinical trials or are expected to be advanced to clinical trials in 2017. Many of these novel therapeutic candidates in the clinic are believed to be first-in-class molecules.  By leveraging our discovery and development technologies and our insights into cancer biology, we have established an extensive and diversified pipeline and formed strategic alliances with pharmaceutical company partners around a number of targets and cancer pathways.

 

•

Advance our therapeutic candidates in clinical trials to determine their utility as treatments for cancer. Our Phase I clinical trials are designed to establish the maximum tolerated dose, safety, identify a therapeutic index and look for initial indications of efficacy and biomarker effects of our drugs alone or as part of a combination regimen. Our Phase II clinical trials are intended to test the efficacy of our drugs in combination with standard-of-care chemotherapy versus the standard of care alone in a randomized, blinded study design.  Results from both of these types of trials serve to inform the next stages of development and trial design. Across our pipeline, we currently have 14 clinical trials underway. In addition, we expect to submit an IND application for GITRL-Fc, a wholly owned immuno-oncology therapeutic candidate to which we have worldwide rights, in the first half of 2017.

 

•

Collaborate with our partners, GSK, Bayer, and Celgene, to advance specific programs forward in clinical development. We are working closely with our partners to advance our partnered programs in development. Under our collaborations, GSK, Bayer and Celgene have certain options during certain time periods through the end of specified Phase I or Phase II trials to obtain exclusive licenses to certain of our antibody or protein-based therapeutic candidates. In the event that these options are not exercised at the end of the relevant option periods, we will have worldwide rights to these programs. Our GSK collaboration is focused on tarextumab. Our Bayer collaboration is focused on the Wnt pathway and includes vantictumab, ipafricept and a small molecule discovery program. Our Celgene collaboration currently includes four programs in clinical development: demcizumab, navicixizumab, anti-RSPO3 and anti-TIGIT.

 

•

Utilize biomarker approaches to identify subsets of cancer patients most likely to benefit from our therapies. In some of our programs, such as tarextumab, brontictuzumab, vantictumab and anti-RSPO3, we have identified potential predictive biomarkers that may assist in patient selection. In other programs, such as demcizumab, navicixizumab, ipafricept, GITRL-Fc and TIGIT, we have extensive biomarker identification/validation research ongoing. We are developing these biomarkers for all of our programs to potentially utilize those biomarkers in late-stage trials to identify patients most likely to benefit from treatment and improve patient outcomes. Where biomarker approaches are successfully utilized in clinical testing, we may elect to develop companion diagnostics in conjunction with suitable third-party development and commercialization partners.

 

•

Use collaborations with pharmaceutical and biopharmaceutical companies to provide funding, create value and leverage partners’ expertise to bring medicines to patients. To facilitate the capital-efficient development and commercialization of our wholly-owned programs, we routinely engage in partnering discussions with a range of pharmaceutical and biopharmaceutical companies. We believe that our existing collaborations with GSK, Bayer and Celgene provide validation of our scientific approach,

7

 

 

significant funding to advance our pipeline and access to development and commercial expertise for our partnered assets.

Since our founding in August 2004, we have raised $772.0 million, consisting of $399.5 million in the form of collaboration funding from our pharmaceutical partnerships, $371.3 million in the form of equity financings, including partner investments, and $1.2 million in grants.

We believe that our broad, novel pipeline of antibody and protein-based therapeutics, our leadership in the fields of cancer biology and antibody engineering and our experienced scientific, clinical and business management team provide us with distinct advantages that enable us to continue to discover and advance novel anti-CSC and immuno-oncology therapeutics.

Understanding Cancer

Cancer is a leading cause of death worldwide, with approximately 14.1 million new cases reported and 8.2 million deaths associated with the disease in 2012 according to the International Agency for Research on Cancer, or IARC. The IARC has projected that by 2030 there will be over 23 million people annually diagnosed with cancer and over 13 million deaths worldwide. The costs associated with cancer medicines is increasing and is projected to reach $150 billion worldwide by 2020 according to a 2016 report by IMS Institute for Healthcare Informatics.  

Cancer is a broad group of diseases in which cells divide and grow in an uncontrolled fashion, forming malignancies that can invade other parts of the body. In normal tissues, the rates of new cell growth and cell death are tightly regulated and kept in balance. In cancerous tissues, this balance is disrupted as a result of mutations, causing unregulated cell division that leads to tumor formation and growth. While tumors can grow slowly or rapidly, the dividing cells will nevertheless accumulate and the normal organization of the tissue will become disrupted. Cancers can subsequently spread throughout the body by processes known as invasion and metastasis. Once cancer spreads to sites beyond the primary tumor, it is generally incurable. Cancer can arise in virtually any part of the body, with the most common types arising in the breast, lung, prostate, colon and skin. Dysregulated cell growth in vital organs such as the liver, lung or brain can impair their normal function with consequences that may ultimately lead to death.

Chemotherapy, radiation and surgical resection of tumors remain the most common approaches for treating cancer, though the field of cancer treatment is rapidly evolving with the emergence of new targeted therapies, tumor diagnostics and genetic tests and the regulatory approval of new classes of immuno-oncology agents. Checkpoint inhibitors, such as Merck’s pembrolizumab (Keytruda®) and Roche’s atezolizumab (Tecentriq®), target the PD1/PDL1 pathway. This pathway is implicated in poor prognoses in a number of cancers and blocking these receptors appears to restore immune function in the tumor microenvironment. As durable single-agent responses have been achieved with these drugs in select solid tumor indications, new research efforts are underway focused on combining checkpoint inhibitors with other therapeutics to induce deeper and more robust responses. Other immuno-oncology approaches in development include bispecific T-cell engagers, or BiTE, a class of bispecific antibodies that direct functional interaction between T-cells and cancer cells to facilitate cancer cell killing, the use of oncolytic viruses that are genetically engineered to infiltrate cancer cells and result in cell death and various cancer vaccines, including some made from actual cancer cells, antigen vaccines that boost immune system activity and dendritic cell vaccines that increase recognition of tumor-specific antigens by T-cells and natural killer cells. Adding chimeric antigen receptors to patient T-cells, known as CAR-T therapy, to elicit a potent and tumor-specific immune response is another immuno-oncology approach being pursued by several companies.

While heightened vigilance, new diagnostic tests, combination therapies, improved treatment regimens and targeted and immuno-therapies have resulted in better patient outcomes, we believe that there is still a substantial need for agents that improve the treatment of cancer. The clinical benefit and anti-cancer effects of currently approved therapies are often relatively transient or only beneficial among certain subsets of patients, and acquired resistance to therapies remains a significant clinical problem with patients frequently relapsing and the disease metastasizing to distant organs. Though significant strides have been made in survival rates over the past several decades, nearly one-third of cancer patients will die within five years of diagnosis.

8

 

OncoMed’s Research Focus

Our drug discovery efforts focus on addressing biologic targets that are implicated in the growth, resistance, recurrence, and metastasis of cancer. To date, this approach has focused on two categories of interventions: anti-CSC and immuno-oncology therapeutics. OncoMed’s pipeline of clinical- and preclinical-stage therapeutic candidates were identified to selectively block CSC pathways or to stimulate targeted immune responses against tumor cells or disable the tumor’s immune evasion mechanisms. By addressing the fundamental biology underlying cancer’s growth, resistance, recurrence, and metastasis, our novel therapeutic candidates are intended to improve patient outcomes and lead to more durable survival.

 

•

Cancer Stem Cells: CSCs are a subpopulation of tumor cells that share certain properties with normal stem cells; specifically, the ability to proliferate indefinitely and to differentiate into multiple cell types. CSCs are believed to be responsible for tumor growth, recurrence after treatment with conventional therapies and metastatic spread of the disease. CSCs have been shown by us and others to be selectively resistant to cytotoxic chemotherapy, radiotherapy and some targeted therapies, so many of the agents currently utilized for cancer treatment are not effective in targeting and eliminating CSCs. Thus, therapies that effectively produce early clinical responses, as noted by reductions in tumor volume, may nevertheless have limited effectiveness if they spare CSCs, as these cells will ultimately promote disease recurrence and spread. We believe that the inability of current therapies to efficiently eradicate CSCs may be a key reason for the failure of many current treatments to achieve durable clinical responses.

 

•

Immuno-Oncology: The immune system is naturally programmed to seek out and destroy abnormal cells. Cancer is believed to thrive, in part, because of a number of cellular mechanisms that aid in the evasion of immune response. Such mechanisms of immune system evasion include masking or reducing the expression of tumor antigens to avoid detection, recruiting T-cell suppressor cells or releasing inhibitory molecules that suppress immune activation, inducing conditions in the tumor microenvironment that promote tumor cell proliferation and survival, and a number of other factors. Immuno-oncology therapies that overcome immune suppression by stimulating responses directed to cancer cells may be a powerful means of counteracting the cellular mechanisms that enable the growth and spread of tumors. Immuno-oncology agents are rapidly emerging as a potential path to durable and long-lasting responses in certain patients.  

We have built a number of proprietary platform technologies focused on understanding cancer biology to elucidate novel targets, design and optimize our biologics for the sought-after activity and evaluate the effects of our therapeutic candidates in state-of-the-art in vivo models.  Based on early CSC drug discovery efforts, we established expertise in identifying, isolating and monitoring CSCs using specific surface markers and flow cytometry. We develop antibodies against these targets using advanced protein engineering technologies, including antibody humanization, phage display, bispecific antibody and Fc-fusion protein platforms, and our proprietary mammalian display platforms. These protein engineering capabilities are being applied and expanded to our novel immuno-oncology agents, including technology to create linkerless trimers of TNF receptor superfamily ligands.  We believe this technology provides a platform that may enable future discovery of multiple new immuno-oncology therapeutic candidates.  

We test our antibodies in proprietary xenograft models derived from freshly resected human tumors subsequently propagated in mice. We believe these patient-derived models are more representative of the clinical features of human tumors than the cell line-based models used in traditional cancer research. Our models also offer the ability to test the effects of therapeutic candidates on human tumors with varied genetic backgrounds, which in turn facilitates the identification of predictive biomarkers.  As our work in cancer immunotherapy has increased, we have expanded the types of xenograft models we deploy to include syngeneic mouse models and models using mice with humanized immune systems so that we can better understand the potential range of immune system responses to our therapeutic interventions.  A more complete description of some of the proprietary platform technologies that we utilize in our drug discovery efforts is described below under “— Our Proprietary Drug Discovery Platform.”

9

 

Targeting Cancer Stem Cells

The discovery that tumors are made up of heterogeneous cell populations provided a new framework for understanding cancer. Also referred to as “tumor-initiating cells,” CSCs were initially discovered in leukemia, and subsequently discovered by our scientific founders in solid tumors derived from patients with breast cancer. In studies that defined the existence of breast CSCs, human tumor biopsies were obtained and tumor cells were fractionated into distinct subpopulations based on their expression of two surface markers, CD44+ and CD24-. It was then demonstrated that only the minor subpopulation of cells with the CD44+/CD24- phenotype markers was capable of initiating tumor growth when implanted into appropriate host mice, whereas the bulk tumor cells could not grow new tumors. Importantly, the tumors harvested from animals injected with tumor-initiating cells recapitulated the cellular heterogeneity of the original tumor biopsy, demonstrating two important properties of CSCs—their ability to self-renew and their ability to generate differentiated, non-tumorigenic progeny. Using similar approaches, CSCs have since been identified in many other solid tumor types, including cancers of the colon, lung, pancreas, brain and skin. We believe that therapeutic strategies aimed at eliminating CSCs within solid tumors, either specifically or in addition to bulk tumor cells, offer the potential of reducing disease progression and providing durable responses.

 

One of our basic approaches has been to develop antibodies and other protein-based therapeutics that target the extracellular and cell surface proteins that are critical to the activation of CSC pathways. Among these important regulatory signals, we are initially targeting the Notch, Wnt and RSPO-LGR pathways and have discovered multiple candidates with distinct mechanisms against different targets in each of these pathways.

The Notch and Wnt pathways play key roles in embryonic development by regulating the fate of cells and tissues in normal organ development. These pathways have been known to be critical for the maintenance of stem cells and have been linked centrally to cancer. The Notch pathway has also been linked to other biological processes that are being targeted in cancer. For instance, the pathway plays an important role in neovascularization and has been linked to modulation of the immune system, including the regulation of T-cell activation. In addition to the Wnt signaling pathway’s role in stem cell control, proliferation and self-renewal, mutations in the Wnt signaling pathway occur frequently in human cancers, and Wnt signaling results in elevated levels of beta catenin, which is known to be a poor prognosis factor in a number of cancer types. Wnt signaling also controls proliferation, maturation and differentiation of certain immune cells and there is emerging evidence that Wnt signaling may play a role in the immune evasion mechanism of tumors. The RSPO-LGR pathway was identified by OncoMed scientists as a key pathway in adult tissue stem cells and is a positive effector of Wnt signaling linked to the development of cancer.

Our approach to target CSCs has been to (1) develop specific antibodies and other biologics against key extracellular proteins that regulate CSC pathways, (2) characterize these antibodies or other biologics in detail to assess their binding affinities and ability to inhibit the target protein and (3) optimize their biophysical properties to ensure their high quality of production for ultimate development and commercial manufacturing. To support these

10

 

efforts, we have developed an advanced understanding of cancer biology as well as proprietary tools and reagents to aid in the evaluation of candidate antibodies and enhance our understanding of mechanisms underlying pathway inhibition. Through this approach, we have successfully generated specific antibodies that block the Notch, Wnt and RSPO-LGR pathways, and we believe that we were among the first companies to initiate clinical trials with antibodies or other biologics targeting these pathways.

Inhibition of CSC pathways has been shown to result in synergistic inhibition of tumor growth when combined with chemotherapeutic agents. Furthermore, we have shown that inhibition of these stem cell pathways drives differentiation of CSCs toward a non-tumorigenic state. In addition to combining well with traditional chemotherapeutic agents which can address the bulk tumor cells, we believe our anti-CSC therapeutic candidates may be well suited to combinations with immunotherapies. Unlike traditional chemotherapies, which can suppress the immune system, our anti-CSC antibodies leave immune system function intact and, in some instances, may even enhance immune function. We believe that by pushing CSCs into a more differentiated state, certain of our anti-CSC therapeutic candidates may make the CSCs more susceptible to immune system activity.

Thus, CSC-directed agents hold the potential promise of dramatically improving cancer treatment. As a result of our efforts to discover novel antibody and protein-based treatments targeting CSCs, we have seven anti-CSC therapeutic candidates advancing in clinical development.

Tackling Challenges in Immuno-Oncology

Leveraging the body’s own immune system to combat cancer may have several potential benefits over traditional chemotherapy, radiation and targeted therapy approaches. Use of immuno-oncology agents may result in a highly selective targeting of disease, activate immunologic memory that could block the resurgence of tumors, and amplify the effect of other anti-cancer drugs when used as part of a combination regimen. Recently introduced immuno-oncology agents hold promise of improving cancer outcomes, but based on clinical trial results to date limited populations of patients appear to benefit from these agents and there is evidence of serious potential toxicities associated with their use.

We are initially concentrating our immuno-oncology research efforts on several of the key core challenges to activating the immune system to recognize and eliminate tumor cells.  These include: increasing the expression of tumor-specific antigens for immune system recognition, attracting essential immune cells, such as leukocytes, to the tumor and targeting fundamental mechanisms of immune evasion within the tumor microenvironment. We are utilizing our diverse protein engineering capabilities, and our understanding of receptor-ligand biology to create highly differentiated immuno-oncology therapeutics.  

Our first two immuno-oncology clinical candidates are anti-TIGIT and GITRL-Fc trimer. TIGIT blocks T-cells from attacking tumor cells, and shares some properties with the inhibitory protein PD-1.  Our anti-TIGIT therapeutic is intended to activate the immune system through multiple mechanisms and enable substantial anti-tumor activity. We are also advancing a GITRL-Fc fusion protein.  GITRL is a member of the TNF family of ligands and functions to activate the co-stimulatory receptor GITR to enhance T-cell modulated immune responses.  Our GITRL-Fc agent is engineered using a novel single-gene linkerless GITRL trimer which enables effective GITR activation and robust anti-tumor immune response. We maintain a very active research effort in the area of immuno-oncology with earlier-stage research ongoing.

In addition, several of our anti-CSC therapeutic candidates appear to possess immuno-oncology mechanisms of action.  Demcizumab targets Delta-like Ligand 4, or DLL4, on the Notch CSC pathway. Through clinical and preclinical studies, we observed that demcizumab has a multi-pronged mechanism of action, including anti-CSC, dys-angiogenesis and immuno-oncology properties.  Demcizumab’s activity on the immune system is believed to act on the regulation of T-cells through IL-17 and the suppression of monocytic myeloid-derived suppressor cells, or MDSCs. Navicixizumab, our anti-DLL4/VEGF bispecific, maintains demcizumab’s multi-pronged mechanism of action, including the suppression of MDSCs, and combines it with the potent anti-angiogenic effects of anti-VEGF. We have conducted preclinical studies of anti-DLL4 and anti-DLL4 plus anti-VEGF in combination with anti-PD-1 inhibitors and observed synergistic anti-tumor responses and heightened immune cell memory responses that are greater than can be achieved with any of the agents when used alone. Additionally, as new evidence emerges that the Wnt pathway may have a role in immune evasion mechanisms, we are conducting research internally and with

11

 

clinical investigators to ascertain the potential for Wnt signaling inhibition to enhance tumor susceptibility to immune responses or enhance the activity of immuno-oncology agents.

Our Therapeutic Candidates and Preclinical Programs

The following table summarizes the status of, and certain of our plans for, our therapeutic candidates and preclinical programs, each of which will be described and discussed in further detail below. We anticipate potential data readouts for multiple Phase II clinical trials for our lead therapeutic candidates, demcizumab and tarextumab, in the first half of 2017. We also anticipate multiple potential milestones from our strategic alliance partners in the coming years contingent upon such factors as successful advancement and trial results for our therapeutic candidates. The timing of these programs and receipt of these milestones is subject to the risks and uncertainties set forth under the caption “Risk Factors.”

 

Demcizumab (Anti-DLL4, OMP-21M18)

Demcizumab (anti-DLL4, OMP-21M18) is a humanized monoclonal antibody that inhibits Delta-like Ligand 4, or DLL4, in the Notch signaling pathway. We believe demcizumab was the first Notch pathway antibody to enter clinical testing. We have completed and published or presented multiple preclinical studies demonstrating robust anti-tumor and anti-CSC activity in multiple solid tumor types, including pancreatic, lung, breast, colon, melanoma and ovarian cancers. Based on preclinical studies, demcizumab appears to have a multi-pronged mechanism of action: halting CSC growth and reducing CSC frequency, disrupting angiogenesis in the tumor and augmenting anti-tumor immune responses by decreasing MDSCs.  Demcizumab is currently being evaluated in three clinical trials: a randomized Phase II trial in pancreatic cancer, a randomized Phase II trial in non-small cell lung cancer, or NSCLC, and a Phase Ib trial combining demcizumab and pembrolizumab (Keytruda®), an anti-Programmed Death-1, or anti-PD-1 antibody. Demcizumab was granted orphan drug designation for the treatment of pancreatic cancer by the FDA in 2014.

We are currently conducting a randomized Phase II trial known as “YOSEMITE” for demcizumab in combination with standard-of-care gemcitabine and Abraxane® in pancreatic cancer.  In the YOSEMITE trial, progression-free survival, or PFS, outcomes for patients treated with demcizumab administered at 5 mg/kg every

12

 

two weeks for either one (Days 0-70) or two (Days 1-70 and Days 168-238) 70 day truncated courses, in combination with gemcitabine and Abraxane® are being compared to PFS outcomes for patients who received a placebo in combination with the chemotherapy. Secondary endpoints for the Phase II clinical trial include overall survival, or OS, overall response rate, pharmacokinetics and safety. Exploratory biomarker analyses are also planned to be examined. The YOSEMITE clinical trial is being conducted at about 50 sites in the U.S. and internationally.

Two hundred and seven patients were randomized in this three-arm trial which completed randomization in August 2016. In the first half of 2017, we anticipate announcing top-line data, including response rate, PFS, interim OS and safety results.  Subsequent analyses of OS data will be conducted in 2017 at mid-year and again at year-end.

Demcizumab is part of our strategic collaboration with Celgene, which retains an option during certain time periods through the end of certain Phase II clinical trials to obtain an exclusive license to co-develop and co-commercialize demcizumab.  The Phase II YOSEMITE data are expected to form the basis of a demcizumab data package that we intend to present to Celgene for opt-in consideration following the availability of top-line results. OncoMed would be entitled to a $70.0 million opt-in payment if Celgene exercises its option on demcizumab.  Following option exercise, OncoMed and Celgene would co-develop and co-commercialize demcizumab in the U.S., sharing profits 50/50, while Celgene would lead development and commercialization outside the U.S.  Additional details related to our collaboration with Celgene are described below under “–Key Collaboration and License Agreements–Strategic Alliance with Celgene.”

A second Phase II clinical trial, known as “DENALI”, for demcizumab in combination with standard-of-care carboplatin and pemetrexed (Alimta®) in front-line non-squamous non-small cell lung cancer, or NSCLC, is also underway.  In November 2016, we announced that we would discontinue further enrollment in the DENALI trial due to the slow rate of patient enrollment and associated costs. In the first half of 2017, we expect to analyze the response, PFS, interim OS and safety data from the 82 patients enrolled in the randomized, three-arm DENALI trial and provide Celgene with these additional results to support the demcizumab data package. A third Phase Ib clinical trial of demcizumab plus pembrolizumab is ongoing and we anticipate that data from an interim safety analysis of the Phase Ib trial will also be provided to Celgene as part of the demcizumab opt-in data package.  Additional data analyses for each of these studies will be conducted as each trial matures, with planned and final analysis of OS from the DENALI trial at year-end 2017.

In March 2016 we initiated a Phase Ib trial evaluating the combination of demcizumab with pembrolizumab in solid tumor patients. In our preclinical research, the combination of anti-DLL4 and anti-PD-1 was found to have more potent antitumor and enhanced immuno-oncology activity than either agent alone.  In addition to the synergistic anti-cancer immune responses observed, the combination of anti-DLL4 and anti-PD-1 reduced tumor growth in re-implantation experiments, suggesting a more significant memory immune response induced by the combination. We presented our findings on the impact of an anti-DLL4 and anti-PD-1 combination on antitumor immune responses at the American Association of Cancer Research Annual Meeting in 2015.

In 2010, we initiated three Phase Ib clinical trials of demcizumab in combination with chemotherapy based on the single-agent data from our Phase Ia trial and our preclinical data. One trial enrolled first-line locally advanced or metastatic pancreatic cancer patients, assessing the maximum tolerated dose, safety and efficacy of demcizumab in combination with standard-of-care gemcitabine and Abraxane®, a second trial enrolled first-line advanced non-squamous NSCLC patients, assessing the maximum tolerated dose, safety and efficacy of demcizumab in combination with standard-of-care carboplatin and pemetrexed (Alimta®), and a third trial (which was closed due to resource prioritization) enrolled first or second-line colorectal cancer patients, assessing safety and efficacy of demcizumab in combination with standard-of-care folinic acid, fluorouracil and irinotecan, or FOLFIRI chemotherapy.  In 2013, we initiated a Phase Ib/II trial of demcizumab with paclitaxel in patients with platinum-resistant ovarian cancer and the Phase Ib portion of this trial has completed enrollment. As part of a budget and pipeline prioritization effort, we decided in 2016 not to conduct the Phase II portion of this trial.

The Phase Ib dose-escalation and expansion study in first-line advanced pancreatic cancer patients assessed the safety, biomarker, and anti-tumor activity of demcizumab and gemcitabine plus Abraxane® in 32 previously untreated patients with advanced pancreatic cancer.  The updated Kaplan-Meier estimated median progression-free survival was 7.1 months and median overall survival was 12.7 months for patients who received the demcizumab-gemcitabine-Abraxane® combination.  Current standard-of-care treatment for advanced pancreatic cancer with

13

 

gemcitabine and Abraxane®, based on Phase III data included in the Abraxane® package insert, has median progression-free survival of 5.5 months and median overall survival of 8.5 months. Of 28 evaluable patients who received the demcizumab-gemcitabine-Abraxane® combination 14 (50%) had a RECIST partial response (unconfirmed) and 11 (39%) achieved stable disease, resulting in a clinical benefit rate of 89 percent. A RECIST partial response means that there has been at least a 30 percent decrease in the sum of the largest diameters (except for lymph nodes) of measured target lesion tumors, taking as reference the baseline sum of the largest diameters of these same tumors, and that there has been no growth of new or non-target tumor lesions. RECIST stable disease means that there has been less than a 30 percent decrease and no more than a 20 percent increase in the sum of the diameters of measured tumor lesions, taking as reference the smallest sum of measured tumor lesions since treatment started, and that there has been no growth of new lesions or non-target tumors.

The combination of demcizumab and gemcitabine plus Abraxane® was generally well tolerated with fatigue, nausea, vomiting and hypertension being the most common drug related toxicities. Pharmacodynamic analyses demonstrated clear down regulation of Notch pathway gene expression at the Phase II dose of demcizumab. These data from the pancreatic cancer Phase Ib trial were most recently presented at the January 2016 Gastrointestinal Cancers Symposium in San Francisco.

A total of 46 patients were enrolled in the Phase Ib study in first-line metastatic non-squamous NSCLC, with 40 evaluable for efficacy across both cohorts. In 23 advanced-stage patients who received continuous dosing of demcizumab plus standard-of-care chemotherapy 43 percent (10 of 23) were alive past two years, demonstrating prolonged survival in a subset of these patients. Final results for the 23 patients who received truncated dosing of demcizumab plus chemotherapy (including maintenance pemetrexed) continued to show a tail on the survival Kaplan-Meier curve with eight patients (35%) alive between 18 to 37 months since initiating treatment.  Median PFS and OS for the overall population of truncated demcizumab dosed patients were 5.8 months and 11.5 months, respectively. The overall clinical benefit rate was 88 percent. One patient (3%) had a complete response, 19 (48%) had unconfirmed partial responses and 15 (38%) had stable disease as measured by RECIST criteria. Although these data are from a non-randomized open-label Phase Ib clinical trial in small numbers of patients, they suggest that a subset of patients treated with the demcizumab truncated dosing regimen plus carboplatin and pemetrexed followed by pemetrexed maintenance in non-squamous NSCLC may derive long-term benefit.

The regimen of demcizumab-carboplatin-pemetrexed was generally well-tolerated with fatigue, nausea and manageable hypertension being the most common demcizumab-related toxicities. In addition, the Phase II dose of demcizumab shows sustained pharmacodynamic modulation of the Notch pathway in patient samples.  Data from the Phase Ib demcizumab clinical trial of patients with first-line NSCLC were most recently presented at the ASCO Annual Meeting in June 2016.

The initial safety and efficacy data from these demcizumab Phase Ib trials were encouraging, although a few cases of reversible Grade 3 pulmonary hypertension and heart failure occurred in patients who were treated with continuous dosing for a prolonged period of time. As a result, we added new cohorts to these trials to enable the evaluation of a more limited duration of treatment (truncated dosing). Additionally, all patients are being followed with cardiac monitoring using B-type natriuretic peptide, or BNP (an early indicator of cardiotoxicity), and Doppler echocardiography. Cardioprotective medications, such as angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitors or carvedilol, are being administered to patients with rising BNPs. Based on the Phase Ib data, the truncated demcizumab dosing (i.e. 70 days of therapy) and cardiac monitoring strategies appear to have mitigated the risks of cardiopulmonary toxicity. Based on then-available safety data from these Phase Ib trials and from then-available blinded interim safety data from Phase II clinical trials of demcizumab, in January 2016, we announced the December 2015 achievement of a $70.0 million safety milestone from Celgene related to the demcizumab development program.

Tarextumab (Anti-Notch2/3, OMP-59R5)

Tarextumab (anti-Notch2/3, OMP-59R5) is a fully human antibody discovered at OncoMed that binds to both the Notch2 and Notch3 receptors and inhibits signaling by both Notch receptors. Based on preclinical experiments, we believe tarextumab exhibits two mechanisms of action: (1) by downregulating Notch pathway signaling, tarextumab appears to have anti-CSC effects, and (2) by affecting vascular pericytes, tarextumab appears to impact stromal and tumor microenvironment. Tarextumab is currently being evaluated in combination with standard-of-care

14

 

chemotherapy in the Phase II portion of a clinical trial for the treatment of small cell lung cancer.  In January 2015, we received orphan drug status designation from the FDA for tarextumab for small cell lung cancer.

Tarextumab is currently being tested in the randomized Phase II portion of a Phase Ib/II clinical trial known as “PINNACLE” in previously untreated patients with extensive-stage small cell lung cancer. The primary endpoint for the Phase II portion of the PINNACLE trial is PFS.  In the Phase II portion of the PINNACLE trial, PFS outcomes for patients treated with tarextumab administered at 15 mg/kg every three weeks in combination with etoposide and cisplatin or carboplatin are being compared to PFS outcomes for patients who receive placebo in combination with the chemotherapy. Secondary endpoints for the Phase II portion of the PINNACLE clinical trial include OS, overall response rate, pharmacokinetics, safety and other biomarkers. PFS and OS will be assessed using predictive biomarkers for tumor expression of Hes1, Hes6, Hey2 and Hey1, and Notch. The PINNACLE clinical trial is being conducted at about 40 sites in the U.S.

Enrollment of 145 patients in the Phase II portion of PINNACLE was completed in August 2016, and we anticipate that top-line results from this trial, including PFS, OS, biomarker-driven efficacy and safety data, will be available in the first half of 2017. Tarextumab is part of our collaboration with GSK. GSK has the option through the completion of certain Phase II trials to obtain an exclusive license to develop and commercialize tarextumab. We plan to submit a tarextumab data package to GSK in the first half of 2017.  GSK then will have the opportunity to review the data package and consider exercising its option. If GSK exercises its option on tarextumab, OncoMed would be entitled to receive a $25.0 million payment.  GSK would then lead and fully fund further development and commercialization with OncoMed providing input through a joint steering committee.  Additional details related to our collaboration with GSK are described below under “–Key Collaboration and License Agreements–Strategic Alliance with GSK.”

Data from the Phase Ib portion of the PINNACLE trial were most recently presented at the ASCO Annual Meeting in June 2016.  The Phase Ib dose-escalation trial enrolled 27 previously untreated patients with extensive-stage small cell lung cancer to assess the safety, biomarker, and anti-tumor activity of tarextumab in combination with etoposide and platinum-based chemotherapy. Doses of tarextumab ranged from 5 mg/kg to 15 mg/kg and a Phase II combination dose of 15 mg/kg every three weeks was selected. Among 15 patients who received higher doses of tarextumab (at or above 12.5 mg/kg every three weeks) in combination with standard-of-care therapy, median PFS of 5.3 months and median OS of 16 months was achieved. Twenty-one of 27 evaluable patients (78%) achieved RECIST responses and six patients (22%) achieved stable disease for an overall clinical benefit rate of 100 percent. New data were presented indicating that patients whose tumors were high in Hes1, Hes6, Hey2 and Hey1 gene expression showed improved survival compared to those whose tumors were low in these markers.

In the Phase Ib portion of the PINNACLE trial, greater tumor size reductions were observed among those patients who received doses of tarextumab at or above 12.5 mg/kg. On-target adverse events associated with tarextumab included diarrhea, fatigue, nausea and decreased appetite. These were mostly Grade 1 or 2 events, and manageable with supportive care.  No dose-limiting toxicities were observed at the Phase II dose of 15 mg/kg with platinum-based chemotherapy and etoposide.

A second Phase Ib/II clinical trial, known as “ALPINE”, was initiated in 2012 to evaluate tarextumab combined with standard-of-care gemcitabine plus Abraxane® in first-line pancreatic cancer and was subsequently discontinued.  On January 25, 2016, we announced feedback received from a pre-planned interim analysis by the Data Safety Monitoring Board, or DSMB, of the Phase II portion of the ALPINE trial indicating a statistically significant worsening of response rate and PFS in the treatment arm in the overall intent-to-treat population, a negative trend in Notch biomarker subgroups, and a trend to lack of benefit in the treatment arm for OS, regardless of Notch biomarker levels, suggesting a low probability of achieving a statistically significant OS benefit. Following receipt of that feedback, we promptly discontinued patient dosing in the ALPINE trial and proceeded to unblind the study.  Subsequently, we confirmed key findings by the DSMB regarding futility of the ALPINE trial.  Post-hoc, exploratory analyses conducted by us revealed subgroups of patients with decreased survival and a subgroup of patients which appears to exhibit improved survival with tarextumab based on Notch3 overexpression in the tumor. Final data from the Phase Ib portion of the ALPINE trial were presented at the January 2016 Gastrointestinal Cancers Symposium in San Francisco.  

15

 

Following notification of the ALPINE DSMB's January 2016 findings, we initiated interactions with tarextumab clinical investigators, partner GSK, the FDA and the PINNACLE trial's DSMB chairperson to assess potential impact of these results on the overall development program, including the ongoing Phase II PINNACLE trial in small-cell lung cancer patients. PINNACLE trial investigators received an addendum to the informed consent form that included a description of the interim analysis from ALPINE.  The FDA and the PINNACLE DSMB were provided unblinded data from both Phase II trials, a description of our exploratory analysis of the ALPINE results and related trial materials for review. The independent analyses of the FDA and PINNACLE DSMB indicated that the PINNACLE trial could continue under the supervision of the PINNACLE DSMB monitoring for safety and efficacy and that appropriate safeguards are in place. We, our investigators, and patients remain blinded to the PINNACLE trial data.

Vantictumab (anti-Fzd, OMP-18R5)

Our vantictumab therapeutic candidate is a fully human monoclonal antibody that modulates Wnt pathway signaling by binding to Frizzled receptors 1, 2, 5, 7 and 8. In our preclinical models, vantictumab reduces CSC frequency and induces differentiation of tumorigenic cells to cell types that are less tumorigenic and more susceptible to conventional chemotherapy. We have seen strong anti-tumor activity using vantictumab in combination with multiple types of approved therapies in patient-derived xenograft models, including pancreatic, breast, lung, melanoma, hepatocellular, ovarian, colorectal and other cancers.  We have also observed synergies preclinically when vantictumab is combined with taxane-based chemotherapies.  In particular, sequential dosing of vantictumab followed by taxane-based chemotherapy has been shown in our preclinical models to have the greatest anti-tumor effect in multiple tumor models compared to taxane or vantictumab treatment alone. We are now applying these findings in our ongoing Phase Ib clinical trial of vantictumab plus paclitaxel in breast cancer patients.  

We initiated three Phase Ib clinical trials in 2014 in distinct solid tumor indications in combination with standard-of-care therapies, one trial in each of breast cancer, pancreatic cancer, and NSCLC. In 2014, in light of adverse bone events seen in the clinical trials, we voluntarily paused enrollment and dosing in these trials. The FDA placed the vantictumab program on partial clinical hold. We worked with bone experts, investigators, and the FDA, and the partial clinical hold was removed in approximately 90 days. In agreement with Bayer, we discontinued enrollment efforts in the trial in NSCLC and expanded target enrollment in the Phase Ib breast cancer trial in November 2015.

During 2016 we presented data from both of the ongoing Phase Ib clinical trials of vantictumab.  At the 2016 ASCO Annual Meeting, we presented results from 31 patients enrolled in the dose escalation Phase Ib clinical trial of Her2-negative breast cancer to assess the safety and tolerability of vantictumab in combination with paclitaxel. Of the 27 patients evaluable for response, the overall response rate was 33 percent.  Some of the most encouraging anti-tumor responses were observed in patient subgroups with high unmet medical need. Four of eleven (33%) third-line patients achieved partial responses and six of 15 (40%) patients with triple-negative disease achieved partial responses by RECIST criteria.  Historically these subgroups would be expected to be among the least responsive to treatment. Patients whose tumors were high in gene expression for a previously identified six-gene signature biomarker demonstrated improved PFS and OS following treatment compared to those whose tumors were low. Of the 31 patients evaluable for safety, interim results showed that vantictumab did not appear to exacerbate paclitaxel side effects.  The most common toxicities reported were fatigue, constipation, diarrhea and nausea.  No fragility fractures have been observed in the vantictumab Phase Ib study in Her2-negative breast cancer following the implementation of an enhanced bone safety plan of monitoring blood bone markers, bone density and administration of zoledronic acid bone protection in certain patients.  

At the European Society of Medical Oncology, or ESMO, in October 2016, we presented Phase Ib data from the pancreatic cancer clinical trial of vantictumab plus gemcitabine and Abraxane®.  Of the 21 patients evaluable for response, ten patients (48%) achieved partial response and another eight achieved stable disease for an overall clinical benefit rate of 86 percent. At the time of the data cut off, PFS and OS data were not yet mature. Exploratory analysis of baseline tumors suggested a three-gene predictive biomarker successfully identified patients with better overall responses. Of the eight patients whose tumors were positive for the biomarker, seven achieved partial responses and one achieved stable disease. Interim safety results showed that the combination of vantictumab with chemotherapy was well tolerated. The most common vantictumab-related toxicities were fatigue, nausea and dysgeusia. No Grade 4 or 5 vantictumab-related toxicities were observed.  Further, vantictumab did not appear to

16

 

enhance chemotherapy-related toxicities. No fragility fractures have been observed in the vantictumab Phase Ib study in pancreatic cancer following the implementation of an enhanced bone safety plan of monitoring blood bone markers, bone density and administration of zoledronic acid bone protection in certain patients.

Vantictumab is part of our collaboration with Bayer. Bayer has an option to obtain an exclusive license to develop and commercialize vantictumab at any point through the earlier of completion of certain Phase Ib trials or a set date in June 2017. Data from the Phase Ib trials of vantictumab will form the basis for an opt-in data package which we anticipate providing to Bayer in the first half of 2017. If Bayer exercises its option, OncoMed would be entitled to receive a $25.0 million opt-in payment for vantictumab, and Bayer would lead and fully fund further development and commercialization. Additional details related to our collaboration with Bayer are described below under “—Key Collaboration and License Agreements—Strategic Alliance with Bayer.”  

Ipafricept (Fzd8-Fc, OMP-54F28)

Ipafricept is our second Wnt pathway modulator. Ipafricept is a fusion protein, or decoy receptor, containing part of the Fzd8 receptor fused to a human immunoglobulin Fc domain. It has a distinct mechanism of action versus vantictumab, namely, binding Wnt ligands rather than binding Frizzled receptors. Ipafricept has shown evidence of strong anti-tumor activity in solid tumors including pancreatic, breast, hepatocellular, ovarian, colorectal and other cancers, and reduction of CSC frequency in multiple preclinical models, either as a single agent or when combined with approved therapies. As with vantictumab, we have observed significant synergies when ipafricept is combined with taxane-based chemotherapies and sequential dosing of ipafricept followed by taxane-based chemotherapy has resulted in enhanced anti-tumor effect in multiple tumor models.  We are now applying these findings in our ongoing Phase Ib clinical trial of ipafricept plus paclitaxel and carboplatin in platinum-sensitive ovarian cancer patients.

We initiated three Phase Ib clinical trials of ipafricept in 2014:  one in pancreatic cancer in combination with gemcitabine plus Abraxane®, one in ovarian cancer in combination with taxane and platinum chemotherapy, and one in hepatocellular carcinoma, or HCC, in combination with sorafenib. In 2014, in light of adverse bone events seen in the clinical trials, we voluntarily paused enrollment and dosing in these trials. The FDA placed the ipafricept program on partial clinical hold. We worked with bone experts, investigators, and the FDA, and the partial clinical hold was removed in approximately 90 days. In agreement with Bayer, we discontinued the trial in HCC and expanded target enrollment in the Phase Ib ovarian cancer trial in November 2015.

At the 2016 ASCO Annual Meeting, we presented interim results from the Phase Ib trial of ipafricept in combination with paclitaxel and carboplatin in patients with recurrent platinum-sensitive epithelial ovarian cancer. Of 19 patients evaluable for response, eight patients (42%) achieved complete responses and eight patients (42%) achieved partial responses as measured by RECIST criteria for an overall response rate of 84 percent.  An exploratory biomarker analysis described patient tumors with high Wnt activation to be more likely to achieve a complete response to ipafricept with carboplatin/paclitaxel treatment. The combination of ipafricept with chemotherapy was well tolerated. The most common toxicities reported were nausea and fatigue, and ipafricept-related adverse events included neutropenia and hypophosphatemia.  No fragility fractures were observed following the implementation of an enhanced bone safety plan of monitoring blood bone markers, bone density and administration of zoledronic acid bone protection in certain patients.  

Interim data from the Phase Ib trial of ipafricept in combination with gemcitabine and Abraxane® were presented in October at the ESMO 2016 Congress.  Of 18 patients evaluable for response, the overall response rate was 39 percent with seven patients achieving partial response as measured by RECIST criteria.  Another eight patients (44%) achieved stable disease for a clinical benefit rate of 83 percent.  Biomarker analyses indicated that patients with higher expression of Wnt pathway genes at baseline had greater than 40 percent reduction in tumor size compared to those patients with lower Wnt pathway gene expression at baseline, suggesting activated Wnt pathway signaling at baseline may be predictive of patients with a more favorable response to treatment.  Early evidence of durability was observed, with nine patients on study greater than 168 days and two patients on study for greater than one year. PFS and OS data are not yet mature. Interim safety results showed that the combination of ipafricept with chemotherapy was well tolerated and ipafricept did not appear to exacerbate chemotherapy-related toxicities.  The most common toxicities were fatigue, nausea and decreased appetite and vomiting.  No Grade 4 or 5

17

 

ipafricept-related toxicities were observed. No fragility fractures occurred among the patients in the Phase Ib trial following the implementation of an enhanced bone safety plan.

Ipafricept is part of our collaboration with Bayer. Bayer has an option to obtain an exclusive license to develop and commercialize ipafricept at any point through the earlier of completion of certain Phase Ib trials or a set date in June 2017. Updated data from the two Phase Ib trials of ipafricept will form the basis for an opt-in data package which we anticipate providing to Bayer in the first half of 2017 in conjunction with the vantictumab data package. If Bayer exercises its option, OncoMed would be entitled to receive a $15.0 million opt-in payment for ipafricept, and Bayer would lead and fully fund further development and commercialization. In addition, we entered into a manufacturing services agreement with Bayer HealthCare LLC whereby Bayer HealthCare LLC manufactures bulk drug substance for this program.  Additional details related to our collaboration with Bayer are described below under “—Key Collaboration and License Agreements—Strategic Alliance with Bayer.”

Navicixizumab (anti-DLL4/VEGF bispecific, OMP-305B83)

We utilized our proprietary bispecific antibody technology to generate a monoclonal antibody, navicixizumab (anti-DLL4/VEGF bispecific, OMP-305B83) that targets both DLL4 and VEGF. DLL4 is the target for one of our lead therapeutic candidates, demcizumab. VEGF is the target for bevacizumab (Avastin®), which is currently approved and used to treat a number of solid tumors including colorectal, NSCLC, breast, renal cell, brain, cervical, and ovarian cancers and had worldwide revenues of $7.4 billion in 2015. Navicixizumab is designed to inhibit the function of both DLL4 and VEGF and thereby have the potential to induce anti-tumor activity while mitigating certain angiogenic-related toxicities.  Preclinical data of dual DLL4 and VEGF inhibition in xenograft tumor models have demonstrated superior anti-tumor activity compared to either anti-DLL4 or anti-VEGF alone and anti-tumor activity was observed in multiple tumor types including colon, ovarian, breast and pancreatic. We have also observed that navicixizumab induced a down-regulation of vasculature-related genes and decreased vasculature density.  An improved cardiac safety profile was also observed in cynomolgus monkeys compared to anti-DLL4.  

We presented first-in-human data from a Phase Ia clinical trial of single-agent navicixizumab at the November 2016 at the 28th EORTC-NCI-AACR Molecular Targets and Cancer Therapeutics Symposium. As of the data cut off of October 17, 2016, a total of 51 patients with advanced solid tumors had received single-agent doses ranging from 0.5 to 12.5 mg/kg every three weeks.  Single-agent anti-tumor activity was observed and navicixizumab was safe enough to be administered on a continuous basis. Two of the 46 patients (4%) evaluable for anti-tumor effects had unconfirmed partial responses, while another sixteen (35%) patients achieved stable disease. The partial responses occurred in patients with ovarian cancer and uterine carcinosarcoma.  Five of eight (63%) evaluable ovarian patients had reductions in tumor volume and remained on therapy ranging from 129 to greater than 323 days as of the data cut off. Navicixizumab was generally well tolerated with hypertension, headache, fatigue and pulmonary hypertension being the most common drug-related toxicities. Hypertension side effects were successfully managed with a protocol-defined anti-hypertensive regimen and most pulmonary hypertension adverse events were reversible and of mild to moderate severity, although a few cases of Grade 3 pulmonary hypertension occurred.  A dose of 7.5 mg/kg once every three weeks was selected for the Phase Ia expansion cohort.

We have initiated two Phase Ib clinical trials to assess the safety, preliminary efficacy, immunogenicity and pharmacokinetics of navicixizumab in combination with standard of care chemotherapy in ovarian and colorectal cancers. A Phase Ib multicenter, open-label, dose-escalation and expansion trial in ovarian cancer will combine navicixizumab with paclitaxel and is expected to enroll approximately 30 patients with platinum-resistant ovarian cancer (including fallopian tube or primary peritoneal cancers) who have previously received bevacizumab and/or have failed at least two prior therapies.  The Phase Ib trial of our navicixizumab in combination with FOLFIRI chemotherapy in colorectal cancer is also expected to enroll approximately 30 patients with metastatic colorectal cancer who have failed first-line treatment, typically bevicizumab plus folinic acid, fluorouracil and oxaliplatin, or FOLFOX, chemotherapy.

Like demcizumab, navicixizumab may also enhance the activity of anti-PD1 therapy.  We presented preclinical data for anti-DLL4 combined with anti-VEGF and anti-PD-1 during the Society for Immunotherapy of Cancer (SITC) Conference in November 2015. A series of preclinical experiments compared the impact of anti-DLL4 plus anti-VEGF and a triple blockade of DLL4, VEGF, and PD-1 on anti-tumor immune responses. The combination of anti-DLL4, anti-VEGF and anti-PD-1 was found to have more potent anti-tumor and enhanced

18

 

immuno-oncology activities than any of these agents alone based on a number of measures. The triple blockade of DLL4-VEGF-PD-1 significantly inhibited tumor growth with more pronounced tumor regression. The addition of anti-DLL4 and anti-VEGF also improved anti-tumor activity of anti-PD-1 alone in both anti-PD-1 responsive and non-responsive cancers in murine models.

Navicixizumab is part of our strategic collaboration with Celgene. Celgene retains an option during certain time periods through the end of certain Phase I clinical trials to obtain an exclusive license to co-develop and co-commercialize navicixizumab. If Celgene exercises its option to navicixizumab, we would be entitled to receive a $25.0 million opt-in payment. Upon option exercise, we and Celgene would co-develop and co-commercialize navicixizumab in the U.S., sharing profits 50/50, while Celgene would lead development and commercialization outside the U.S.  Additional details related to our collaboration with Celgene are described below under “—Key Collaboration and License Agreements—Strategic Alliance with Celgene.”

Anti-RSPO3 (OMP-131R10)

In 2007, we identified that the R-spondin, or RSPO, ligands signal through the LGR receptor family and have since identified antibodies to proteins in this family that modulate RSPO-LGR signaling. RSPO appears to be an oncogenic driver in several tumor types, particularly colon cancer. RSPO is associated with the activation of Wnt signaling and tumorigenesis. Anti-RSPO3 (OMP-131R10) is our lead program targeting the RSPO-LGR pathway. We have developed a strong biomarker hypothesis associated with this program, which has entailed the custom development of an assay that tests RSPO3 elevated gene expression and a liquid biopsy assay that looks for gene fusions.  We are now utilizing both of these tests in our ongoing clinical trial in order to prospectively identify patients who may be more likely to respond to treatment.

In preclinical studies anti-RSPO3 antibody demonstrated robust in vivo anti-tumor efficacy as a single agent and in combination with standard of care across a range of solid tumors, including colon, lung, ovarian, and pancreatic cancers, among others. The anti-RSPO3 antibody delayed tumor recurrence following termination of chemotherapy, and decreased the frequency of CSCs.  

We initiated a Phase Ia/b solid tumor trial of anti-RSPO3 (OMP-131R10) in July 2015, initially enrolling patients with advanced refractory solid tumors. The open-label study is designed to assess the safety, pharmacokinetics, pharmacodynamics and initial evidence of efficacy of the anti-RSPO3 antibody.  Biomarker-selected patients are currently being enrolled in a Phase Ia expansion arm to obtain additional preliminary information on possible anti-tumor activity. In the Phase Ib portion of the trial initiated in January 2016, anti-RSPO3 is being tested in patients with certain colorectal and gastric cancers in combination with FOLFIRI.

First-in-human interim data from the Phase Ia/b clinical trial were presented at the 28th EORTC-NCI-AACR Molecular Targets and Cancer Therapeutics Symposium in November 2016. As of the data cut-off date of October 11, 2016, 23 patients in the anti-RSPO3 Phase Ia/b clinical trial were evaluable for safety and 15 patients were evaluable for anti-tumor activity.  In the single-agent Phase Ia portion of the trial, five of eleven patients (45%) achieved stable disease and three of those five patients were RSPO3 high, with RSPO3 levels in a fourth patient slightly below the current cut point of our CLIA-validated biomarker assay.  Three of the stable disease patients in the Phase Ia portion of the trial demonstrated prolonged stable disease of greater than 112 days as of the data cut off. In the Phase Ib portion of the trial, three of four evaluable subjects (75%) who received the combination of anti-RSPO3 and FOLFIRI achieved stable disease. Anti-RSPO3 was generally well tolerated as a single agent with the most common adverse events being fatigue and nausea. Among seven safety-evaluable Phase Ib colorectal cancer patients who received anti-RSPO3 in combination with FOLFIRI the combination did not appear to exacerbate the toxicities of either drug.  

Programs in the RSPO-LGR pathway are part of our strategic collaboration with Celgene. Upon the completion of certain enrollment objectives in the current Phase Ia/b clinical trial, we intend to submit a data package to Celgene for opt-in consideration. If Celgene exercises its option on anti-RSPO3, we would be entitled to receive an approximately $37.8 million opt-in payment.  Upon option exercise, we and Celgene would co-develop and co-commercialize anti-RSPO3 in the U.S., sharing profits 50/50, while Celgene would lead development and commercialization outside the U.S.  Additional details related to our collaboration with Celgene are described below under “—Key Collaboration and License Agreements—Strategic Alliance with Celgene.”

19

 

Brontictuzumab (Anti-Notch1, OMP-52M51)

Our anti-Notch1 antibody, brontictuzumab, is a humanized monoclonal antibody, and has shown substantial activity in Notch-dependent tumors in preclinical studies.

Two single-agent Phase Ia trials have been conducted for brontictuzumab, one in hematologic malignancies and one in solid tumors. We ceased development of brontictuzumab in hematologic malignancies in 2015, following completion of the Phase Ia trial.

Data from the solid tumor Phase Ia trial were presented in an oral plenary session at the AACR-NCI-EORTC International Conference on Molecular Targets and Cancer Therapeutics in November 2015. Brontictuzumab demonstrated single-agent activity in a biomarker-selected refractory patient population. Among 15 patients whose tumors overexpressed the activated form of Notch1, as measured by our proprietary immunohistochemistry (IHC) test, eight patients achieved stable disease or partial response for an overall clinical benefit rate of 53 percent. In a subsequent update, nine patients achieved stable disease or partial response for overall clinical benefit rate of 56 percent. Anti-tumor activity was observed in adenoid cystic carcinoma, colorectal cancer and HER2 negative breast cancer. Among 15 patients whose tumors measured high in Notch1 activation, five (33%) survived 100 days or longer as of the data cut off. In biomarker negative subjects, only one of 11 had clinical benefit (9%). Brontictuzumab was generally well tolerated, with the most common adverse event being on-target, manageable diarrhea.  Notch pathway and CSC pathway markers were reduced in surrogate patient samples (blood) at doses above 1.5 mg/kg every three weeks.  The single agent Phase II dose of brontictuzumab was established as 1.5 mg/kg every three weeks.  

Brontictuzumab was originally part of our collaboration with GSK. On October 31, 2016, GSK provided written notice to us that it was terminating its option to obtain an exclusive license to develop and commercialize brontictuzumab in order to focus the collaboration on the tarextumab program. This termination became effective on January 29, 2017 and we now have worldwide rights to brontictuzumab.

In January 2017, we initiated a Phase Ib clinical trial of brontictuzumab in combination with trifluridine/tipiracil (Lonsurf®).  The Phase Ib trial is designed to assess safety, preliminary efficacy and immunogenicity, as well as predictive and pharmacodynamics biomarkers.  Metastatic colorectal cancer patients who have received at least two prior lines of therapy will be enrolled in the dose-escalation portion of the trial, and once a maximum tolerated dose is identified, additional patients whose tumors test high for the activated form of Notch1 will be enrolled in an expansion cohort.  

Anti-TIGIT (OMP-313M32)

TIGIT blocks T-cells from attacking tumor cells, similar to the inhibitory protein PD-1.  Our anti-TIGIT therapeutic is intended to activate the immune system, through multiple mechanisms, and enable anti-tumor activity.  In December 2016, we filed an IND application with the FDA for anti-TIGIT. A Phase I clinical trial of anti-TIGIT is expected to begin enrolling patients during the first half of 2017.
